[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The UK Parliament Note 156 dated June 2001 looked at human factors which are liab
[normal]le to cause such errors, examines
[normal]how their effects can be minimised and analysed the implications for health and safety policy
[normal].  Readers of this note may falsely assume that investment into human factors in the GB railway 
[normal]during the last thirteen years 
[normal]m
[normal]ay have led to safety risk reduction in the GB railway industry. The continuous stream of level crossing and track worker accidents draw our attention to the fact the operating and maintenance 
[normal]rules
[normal], and signalling
[normal] 
[normal]procedures still
[normal] suffer from latent human
[normal] factors issues. Moreover, the UK Parliament Note 156 did not look at the human errors that may occur in the method of risk and accident analysis deployed by the GB railway industry. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Research conducted in 1974 by William Johnson and his team found that v
[normal]arious acts of omission and commission in industrial organisations 
[normal]can 
[normal]lead to accidents. They developed a logical tree representation called Management Oversight and Risk Tree to perform what is known as post-mortem analysis of accident to learn what went
[normal] wrong and inform 
[normal]decision making based upon the MORT representation
[normal] (Kingston, et al., 2004)
